    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-10-14T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-10-14T07:00:00-05:00" n="638"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d638">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 165.102/167</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                    <placeName>
                        <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi>
                    </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-10-14T13:00:00+01:00">
                        <hi rend="italic">October 14, 1914, 1 p.m.</hi>
                    </date>
                    <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received October 15, 3 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                <p>505. The German Government and exporters must have guarantee our Government that
                    goods shipped on the <hi rend="italic">Matanzas</hi> shall not be reexported. I
                    have already suggested in cable of September 26 that Department of Commerce and
                    Labor be charged with duty of seeing that none of goods are used except in the
                    United States and Mexico. Guarantee of individuals and companies not
                    sufficient.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
